A Czech referees the fight for the seabed
It approaches a wall-mounted electronic map, showing Australia and adjacent marine areas.
However, he is not interested in the continent, but in a small point lost in the blue of the ocean.
"The island belongs to Australia, as does the adjacent seabed.
Yet this area is as large as the continent itself," says Italian jurist Luigi Santosuosso, who is part of the team of thirty members of the UN Division for Ocean Affairs and the Law of the Sea.
Its head, the director of the division, Czech jurist Václav Mikulka, follows the presentation and completes it from time to time.
Ardour at work and enthusiasm characterize the prevailing atmosphere.
The seabed hides a little-known world so far, rich in natural resources.
There may be oil, minerals and other mineral resources, but also living organisms unknown at the moment, which may hold the key to the development of a drug against cancer.
A background larger than the dry land
The littoral states have today begun to vehemently aspire to the new underwater territories.
According to a UN convention, they are in fact using their rights, on which they agreed in 1982 in Montego Bay, Jamaica.
This is mainly the area of what is called the continental shelf, which often extends several hundred kilometers from the coast of the given country.
The latter may, according to the convention, claim exclusively all the resources of the continental shelf.
For simplicity, the part of the seabed and its subsoil, which is a natural extension of the continent under the sea, is considered as continental shelf.
It extends beyond the limits of the littoral sea, often also beyond the two hundred nautical miles that represent the so-called exclusive economic yone,” explains Mikulka.
The request that the country in question submits to the Commission for the establishment of the external borders of the continental shelf, must be supported by a large scientific and technical documentation, based on many surveys and costly metrics.
It is the result of several years of preparatory work.
"One of our roles is to provide the committee with legal and scientific-technical assistance.
So far, the committee has dealt with five requests, from Russia, Brazil, Australia, Ireland and New Zealand.
So far, only the last three countries mentioned have been successful,” Mikulka adds.
The success of Australia, which was the first to significantly expand its underwater holdings, has recently had a global impact.
New Zealand, too, has gained territory - the extent of the seabed, which the commission attributed to it last week, corresponds to 1.6 million square kilometres, which is the country's extent multiplied by six.
Both countries have invested millions of dollars in prospecting.
The benefits they will derive in the future from the exploitation of the seabed will, as they project, be invaluable.
Gradually, other countries will, in turn, submit their applications.
They can do so within ten years of ratifying the "Montego Bay Convention".
There, where the continental shelf ends, begins the area of the ocean floor, proclaimed by convention "common heritage of humanity".
There, no longer any state enjoys an exclusive position.
The right of extraction in this area is granted by an international institution established by convention.
"Nevertheless, make no mistake, the seabed is not a Klondike," Mikulka said, exaggerating, adding that "its areas are precisely clearly defined and their regime anchored in a contract."
Czechs in the Pacific
Today, part of the seabed also belongs to the Czech Republic.
It shares it with other states of the former Eastern Bloc within the framework of the joint organization "Interoceanmetal".
In 1991, under the Convention, the Commission, together with investors from a few other States, obtained the status of a so-called "pioneer investor".
It has the right of extraction in the ClarionClipperton zone in the Pacific Ocean, located between Mexico, the Hawaiian Islands and Kiribati.
The area prospected by the investor slightly exceeds the area of the former Czechoslovakia.
The background is turbulent, it is a kind of underwater replica of the Tatra.
“It is possible to extract it over an area with a total area of 75,000 square kilometers.
The area represents a deposit rich in polymetallic concretions containing nickel, copper, cobalt and manganese," said Ind Pakshi Rajan, another jurist.
Rober Sandev, a Macedonian employee of the division, provides an example of such a concretion.
