Organizers report a growing number of bookings
This should be a good winter for German travel agencies:
In terms of bookings for the coming months, according to a study, the turnover has increased significantly compared to the previous year - for the winter season, even more than 30 percent.
Despite the weak economic outlook, the Germans’ thirst for travel remains insatiable according to this study.
With regard to bookings for the winter season, travel agencies recorded a turnover of more than 31 percent compared to the same period the previous year, as entrusted Monday in Berlin by the German Federation of Travel Agencies (DRV).
According to the survey by the GfK Market Research Institute, increasing booking figures are already dominating the autumn months.
Thus the sales figure would have risen to about more 11 percent compared to 2007, said DRV.
The sources of these results are figures from GfK, which analyses monthly booking data from 1200 travel agencies and makes estimates for the overall market.
Travel bookings made since the end of August 2008 would be recorded there.
Due to the low price of the dollar, travel to the U.S. would be particularly in demand, the DRV said.
There, the increase in bookings would amount to about one-third.
Besides this, Spain, Turkey and Greece as well as our country would be destinations particularly sought after by the Germans.
Specially organized trips are in high demand, explained the president of DRV Klaus Laepple.
In view of the rising prices of energy and food products, the costs here would be "more easily calculated for the customer than for an individually organized trip".
Consumers can save money, among other things, with discounts on early bookings or All Inclusive offers, Laepple explained.
The summer months have also been very successful so that an increase in sales figures will again be recorded compared to last year - although according to another study, the number of Germans who undertook a trip has decreased compared to the previous year.
