Morgan Stanley opens its capital to MUFG
Morgan Stanley has announced the entry in its turn of Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group (MUFG), the first bank of Japan, which will disburse nine billion dollars to take 21% of its capital, a news welcomed by a sharp drop in its stock market price.
A week after unveiling a tentative deal, the two banks explained that MUFG would buy 9.9% of Morgan Stanley common shares at a unit price of $25.25, a total of $3 billion.
The retained price is 19% lower than the book value of the securities as at 31 August.
MUFG will invest an additional $6 billion in the acquisition of convertible securities with a return of 10% and a conversion price of $31.25.
Morgan Stanley said the overall transaction would be based on an average unit price of $29, or 28 percent above its current price.
Morgan Stanley was down 6.79% at $23.07 around 17:00 GMT.
“This strategic alliance is an important opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley’s transition to banking holding status,” said John Mack, Morgan Stanley’s chief executive officer.
Morgan Stanley adopted this new status last week, which should allow it to diversify its activities but puts it under the authority of the Federal Reserve.
Its alliance with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis is forcing the biggest names on Wall Street to adopt a much more cautious attitude than before.
The terms presented on Monday also show that the agreement has been modified in recent days: last Monday, Morgan had simply announced that it would sell up to 20% of its shares to the Japanese for about $ 8.5 billion.
“A week ago,” Toshihide Mizuno, MUFG’s executive director, told Tokyo, “we thought the stake would be made up entirely of common shares.
But given the current situation of the economy and the market, we wanted to minimize the risks and cover ourselves."
Based on the weighted average price, MUFG will pay its Morgan Stanley securities 7% below their book value.
And the deal will result in a dilution of about 20% of earnings per share.
Under the agreement, MUFG will be able to convert half of its preferred securities into common shares within a year if they trade more than 50 percent above the conversion price, or about $47, over a period of time.
Morgan Stanley said the capital provided by MUFG will enable it to seize investment opportunities, strengthen its balance sheet and increase liquidity.
A spokeswoman for the group, however, declined to elaborate on the strategic plans of the two new allies.
Following the MUFG investment, Morgan Stanley is expected to have a Tier One solvency ratio of around 15%, one of the best in the industry.
Morgan said it had "clearly" reduced its balance sheet since the end of August.
The past few weeks have been trying for the group, which has seen its stock price halve as the cost of insurance against a default risk on its debt soared.
This cost was declining on Monday but remained at a high level, around 12%.
Last week, Goldman Sachs, the only other “survivor” of the big Wall Street investment banks after the bankruptcies of Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers and the takeover of Merrill Lynch, announced it had raised $15 billion, in part from Warren Buffett’s Berkshire Hathaway group.
Rafael Correa in Quito on Monday.
Refounding the republic around the socialism of the 21st century.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, like his counterparts and friends, it is the third that put to the vote a draft of the new Constitution.
64% of voters voted “yes” in the referendum, according to official results for 80% of the vote.
According to these results, the "no" got 28%, 7% of the votes were null and 0.7% were white votes.
In order for the draft Constitution to be adopted, it had to get half of the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two polls conducted outside polling stations and a tally from a non-governmental organization had announced a wide victory of "yes", placing it between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had claimed in the night of Sunday to Monday the victory of his draft of Constitution.
The "constitution has triumphed overwhelmingly," he assured, congratulating Ecuadorians at the headquarters of the governorate of Guayaquil, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
As of course, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chavez and Morales but also his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The election, which took place quietly according to the observer mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), focused on a text in 444 points consolidating the "new socialism" defended by the president.
The draft Constitution enshrines the power of the state over the economy, reserving for it the "development planning" of a country living essentially from the extraction of oil by foreign companies and the currencies sent by its emigrants.
Supported by Correa, who was elected in 2006, the project also grants the head of state enhanced powers, who will be able to serve up to two consecutive four-year terms and will have the opportunity to dissolve the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he will use that power and seek a new term in February 2009.
The Constitution also consolidates the principle of free health and education services that the President has begun to establish in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
It also provides for a ban on the presence of foreign troops, which will end the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for U.S. anti-drug operations.
All 19 hostages released in Chad
An Egyptian commando launched the assault against the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight companions captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions held captive for ten days in the desert were brought safely back to the Egyptian capital on Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they had been released by an Egyptian commando in Chad.
Apparently in good shape, the hostages arrived at about 3:30 p.m. on a special plane at the al-Maza military base, next to Cairo International Airport.
They were immediately transferred, without being able to speak to the press, on helicopters to the hospital in Maadi, a residential suburb of Cairo, for examinations.
They are in "good health" and "no ransom has been paid" to the kidnappers, Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garanna said on the tarmac.
Captured on September 19 during a 4x4 safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, this group of hostages had been tossed from one cache to another by 35 unknown kidnappers.
It includes 11 tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - as well as eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the agency Aegyptous, organizer of the safari.
An Egyptian security official said 30 members of the special forces, flown aboard two helicopters, had launched the assault in the night just before dawn.
"An exchange of gunfire occurred, and half of the abductors were killed, the others fleeing," the official said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
He said that a total of 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the “lightning” unit had been sent to Sudan, where they received support from German and Italian commandos.
Italian Foreign Minister Franco Frattini mentioned from Belgrade, where he is, the role played by secret agents and elements of the Italian special forces.
"We must recognize that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of our intelligence, special forces men," he said, without elaborating.
He also denied paying a ransom.
The day before, the Sudanese army claimed to have intercepted a 4x4 vehicle with the abductors on board, killing six, including the Chadian leader, and arresting two.
The army claimed they were linked to a Darfur rebel group, the Sudan Liberation Movement-Unity (SLA-U), which the movement immediately denied.
Letters - The Silent Majority of Culture
A debate on the financing of culture is making headlines and occupying the current election campaign.
All the better.
But one area of our cultural life is still forgotten.
Who will stand up to denounce the sums of misery that are given to small museums, archives, archaeological excavations or national historic sites that are dying of hunger?
What politician will dare to remind the federal government that it neglects its monuments and heritage buildings?
That in Quebec, as in Canada, we do not have real laws that effectively preserve our heritage?
Did you know that the French government is devoting three and a half million euros to the restoration of the only Ch<0xC3><0xA2>teau de Chinon in the Loire Valley?
Among our American neighbors, it is written in the Constitution of their country that the protection of heritage is part of the culture of Americans and that this heritage must be protected by all citizens, all elected officials and all government departments, and this, in consultation.
In Quebec, the Fédération des sociétés d'histoire du Québec, at least 40,000 volunteers from 211 historical, heritage, archival and genealogical societies are concerned with excavating history, preserving three under heaps of private archives and preserving archaeological remains.
It is they, often, who are the watchdogs of our heritage, who protest with the energy of despair when promoters and decision-makers throw their bulldozers at our old stones and forgotten cemeteries.
When, a forum for history and heritage?
Benelux governments nationalize part of Fortis bank
The Benelux states are helping the Belgian-Dutch bank, as the first European bank in distress following the snowball effect of the credit market crisis in the United States, by partially nationalizing it. The three countries support, to the tune of 11.2 billion euros, this financial and insurance institution also having interests in Hungary.
This weekend, the Belgian, Luxembourg and Dutch governments agreed, at the highest level, on this case, also calling on the European Central Bank and the head of competition of the European Commission.
In the euro area, the first major crisis in the context of the international financial crisis, which has been escalating for more than a year, is for Fortis Bank. From a certain point of view, the decisions that will be taken in the case of this bank will serve as a precedent.
In accordance with the decision taken on Sunday night, the three states will buy back nearly half (up to 49%) of the capital of the bank located in each of the countries.
The bank will, no doubt, sell a part of its stakes, among which, first of all, the activities, mainly insurance, which it acquired last year from the Dutch organization ABN Amro.
In the second half of the week, serious signs of crisis have already been revealed at the bank.
Analysts agree that with its 85,000 employees, the bank is far too big to be allowed to go bankrupt.
On Friday alone, the company’s shares fell 12 percent to their lowest level of 14 years ago.
Since January, stocks have fallen by more than two-thirds of their value.
Taking into account the current value of the shares, the total value of the capital of the group is around 14 billion euros, which, according to the company's executives, is not realistic.
The management of the company accuses the uncertainty across the Atlantic, in connection with the adoption of the US rescue plan of $ 700 billion, to be at the origin of the fall of the Fortis shares.
On Monday, the papers have already benefited from a slight increase.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed as the bank’s new chief executive officer.
The financial institution was also looking for private buyers, but has not yet received a proposal on the merits.
Previously, the Belgian government announced that investors should not worry, they were not going to lose their money.
No panic was felt in the bank’s customer circle and no agency was stormed.
In Hungary, Fortis has independent agencies and has also acquired leasing companies.
A fox in the chicken coop
In America, life and health insurance companies frequently refuse to sign an insurance contract with an applicant, based on information about his or her drug purchases.
Information protection experts fear the data market will spiral out of control.
"There are data protection programs that link the use of information regarding the prescription of medicines, in any case, to the consent of the person concerned.
This kind of program has to be in independent hands, otherwise it’s like putting your chicken coop in the hands of a fox,” Richard Dicket, the creator of the program used to manage prescription drugs, told the Washington Post.
Insurance companies depend on the insurance premium and the insured capital in case of damage, on the state of health of the client who presents himself, and if they consider that the risk is too great, they do not even insure it.
In the past, they sent candidates for a medical examination, and they only signed an insurance contract with them after learning the results.
For the past ten years, Dick has found a much cheaper procedure: from an identification number, data on the person's drug purchases in the past eighteen months is easily provided to pharmacies. From this, the program determines itself, from which disease the person suffers and what is his state of health.
For example, if this person regularly buys high doses of cholesterol reducer, this refers to an extremely high level of fat in the blood, which immediately puts them in a higher risk category.
Several versions of this program are in circulation. Some determine at the same time a risk factor, so there is not much left to do to the insurer apart from the paperwork. However, tiny problems can still appear.
Disadvantages of this program include the fact that a drug can be used for different purposes. For example, some mixtures can be used against migraine or hot flashes, but can also be effective against depression.
The latter is considered by insurers as an aggravating risk factor, while the others are not.
Companies have developed in the research and analysis of data. They must seek permission from the patient before collecting necessary information from the pharmacy.
From now on, they are forced to do so by the authorities, even if they have not been punished for their failures in the past.
Recently, some companies have also been processing the results of laboratory analyses and linking them with data on drug use, thus being able to provide an even more accurate picture of patients' health status.
More and more companies have access to data, and controlling usage is becoming increasingly difficult.
There is a separate law on the protection of medical data, but its scope of action extends only to practitioners and insurers.
A bill to widen the circle of control of the authorities concerning companies specializing in the provision of data is currently before Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is not enough and that is why he has further developed his program, which would condition the transmission of data on the exclusive consent of the person concerned.
This is another question of whether the person concerned is really free to give his consent or not, since if he refuses, the insurance companies do not sign an insurance contract with him.
So, in the end, the hens depend on the benevolence of the fox.
The global menu of Marseille
The European Union and India are doubling their trade.
Since the European Union and India are very important trading partners for each other, this topic also dominated the agenda of this ninth summit alongside the other, largely global, issues.
Today, a France-India summit will also take place, where cooperation in the field of atomic energy will be discussed.
The European Union recognises that India is a major emerging democratic power that should be given a broader say in international affairs, but member countries have yet to agree on their support for New Delhi for its candidacy as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
They did not dwell too much on this issue, yesterday, at this 9th summit held in Marseille.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, as well as the current President of the Union, as well as the President of the Commission José Manuel Barroso and the head of diplomacy, Javier Solana, welcomed the Indian Prime Minister, Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed that in five years they would double trade, which means an increase of a good hundred billion.
Taking into account that between 2000 and 2007, trade in goods rose from 25 billion to 55 billion, this does not seem to be an overly ambitious goal.
In this sense, they have legally harmonized the 26 bilateral agreements with India concerning civil flights, so that air traffic can also grow in the future.
India would like to sign a free trade agreement with the EU by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the negotiations.
The aim is to balance the situation with, on the one hand, India, which is the EU's largest trading partner, and, on the other, New Delhi, which is only ninth among the EU's partners.
The summit devoted its attention to global affairs.
The situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan was strongly condemned, as was all forms of terrorism, and there was mention of the urgency of holding a United Nations conference on the subject.
The completion of the Doha trade cycle has also been called for, although both play a large part in the current failure.
The EU has confirmed that it remains committed to the energy and climate agenda, including that it would like to reduce its releases of toxic materials by at least 20 per cent by 2020.
India also agreed on this point, as well as on the need for a global market at the climate conference next year, and to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 50 per cent by 2050.
They would also like to prevent food prices from rising, and supported convening an international working meeting to discuss the financial crisis.
The Indian head of state is visiting the French capital today, where during a bilateral meeting, he is preparing to sign an agreement on the peaceful use of atomic energy.
In Paris, it is hoped that French companies will receive orders worth twenty billion euros for the construction of Indian atomic reactors.
According to the press agency, the agreement would last for 15 years.
In Frankfurt, more than three hundred Italian publishers
Strong presence of Italian publishers at the Frankfurt International Book Fair.
More than three hundred Italian publishers attended the 60th edition of the Buchmesse, the most important international event in the exchange of rights.
The Frankfurt International Book Fair is waiting for this edition, more than 7 thousand exhibitors from 101 different countries who will occupy the 171,790 square meters of the Fair with more than 403 thousand titles on display, and Turkey as the guest of honor.
It will be the Undersecretary of the Ministry of Cultural Heritage and Activities, Francesco Maria Giro, who will represent the Italian Government, at the inauguration ceremony of the Italian Butterfly: indeed, Italy will be present in an institutional way, with an Italy Point - 264 square meters of exhibition space.
It will be followed by the press meeting in the Room Struktur, at butterfly 5.0 of the Buchmesse: an opportunity to present the figures, trends and prospects on the position of publishing in Italy.
According to the data, the importance of foreign author books is gradually decreasing compared to the total of Italian production, and in particular, compared to that for adults and children.
Found the plane of Steve Fossett, the billionaire who disappeared a year ago.
The wreckage of the plane of Steve Fosset, the billionaire disappeared on September 3, 2007 while he was flying over the Nevada desert, has been found.
The debris was found on a plateau 3,000 meters above sea level, in the Sierra Nevada area of Mammonth Lakes, on the border between California and Nevada.
Inside the plane, however, no human remains.
Madera County Sheriff John Anderson said: “The plane was located, we sent a team, and now we have confirmation that this is the one that Steve Fosset was travelling on the day he disappeared.”
The sheriff said no human remains were found on or near the plane.
In February, the 63-year-old billionaire was considered dead.
The U.S. Transportation Safety Board (NTSB) said that a few hours after the wreckage was located, a team of investigators sent to the scene identified the aircraft: it is the Bellanca 8kcab, disappeared on September 3, 2007, when Fosset took off from Yerington in Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, still in California, not far from the border of Nevada, some personal belongings of Fosset were found by a couple around their home in Mammoth Lakes.
These are two documents bearing the name of Fosset, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of Illinois, cash and a sweater.
Fossett's search was halted a month after he disappeared.
The billionaire had earned a place in history thanks to a long series of records.
On the sixth attempt, he had become in 2002, the first man to complete the round the world on an aerostatic balloon: two weeks of solo flight.
Three years later, he had traveled around the world by plane and non-stop.
Among all these records, also that of having flown at 15,445 meters high, on the Andes, but with a co-pilot.
Glk, the publicity you're not expecting.
An unusual 4x4 of an original and well-defined design, with marked lines, wide surfaces and sharp angles.
Here, in synthesis, Glk, the latest off-road "compact" of the house of the star, with which Mercedes-Benz has tried to give a wind of novelty in this sector.
Precisely because of its non-standard, unexpected and unconventional content will be the communication that will accompany the launch of the 4x4 Glk, available in Mercedes-Benz showrooms, from October 17th.
Thus the hype that will accompany the beginning of the new car will give rise to a new mode of communication, through a futuristic campaign of 3D displays, used for the first time in Italy by an automotive brand.
A project of maxi displays, articulated in three different phases, which will dominate the heart of Milanese shopping, Corso Como, until November 15.
The first phase of this new type of communication provides for the presentation of the car in stereoscopic vision, and thanks to special glasses distributed around Corso Como, it will be possible to see the new 4x4 in almost real dimensions and in three-dimensional format.
Indeed, one will have the impression that looking at the image, the car comes out of the poster.
Then, through the use of the innovative Elimina8 technology, the new Glk will be illuminated according to the spots, in all its details, and then recompose into a single image.
It is obvious that with this advertising, Mercedes is trying to introduce something new into the stereotypical field of motoring communication.
Will it succeed with this formula to arouse the interest of future purchasers? We will see.
